In Object-Oriented Programming, we can use delegation to achieve this. Delegation is the process of passing a request from one object (the client) onwards towards another which will handle it and then pass back through an intermediate handler or delegate that handles further processing if necessary for some reason such as in your case you want `List` class's methods available within our new delegated classes.

Here is how we can do this:
```java
class List {   // super-list (delegate) here, it will have all the list related operations and behaviors like add(), remove() etc...
    void displayList(){};     // methods of a delegate class should be public if they are not private or protected. 
}

// Stack is now delegated to List: It can use any method from `list` but also have additional functionality specific for stacks (like push(), pop() etc...)  
class GigaList extends List {    // here, we're extending the delegate class 'GigaList', which inherits all methods of super-delegate. 
     void displayStack(){};      // new method to handle stack operations specific for this list type (like push(), pop() etc...)  
}
```
In your main program, you can use `list` and then call the delegated class's functions:
```java   
public static void main(String[] args) { 
     GigaList g = new GigaList(); // create a list object of type 'Gigalo', which is actually List.  

     /* Calling methods from both classes */
     g.displayStack();      
}   
```
This way, you can use the functionality provided by `list` in your delegated class (in this case GigaList), while still having full control over how and when those operations are performed within that specific list type's context or delegate structure for other classes using List.  This is a common technique used to achieve loose coupling between different parts of an application, as it allows you to change the implementation details (the delegated class) without affecting code in use by clients/users who do not need these changes directly implemented into their existing system architecture and design patterns are often very useful when dealing with such situations.

